{
  "text": "Ten of the studies we included measured troponins, of which three also measured BNP (further details in online supplementary table S1). Of these, seven measured mortality, and an association was found with elevated troponins and increased mortality in all these studies. However, these measured mortality at a variety of different time points, ranging from in-hospital death of admitted patients, to deaths of patients discharged from hospital and followed for a mean of 50 months. Other outcomes measured were repeat hospitalisation [CITATION_1] and length of hospital stay; [CITATION_2] and these papers found a statistically significant association with increased troponin measurements and repeat hospitalisation (HR=2.89, 95% CI 1.13 to 7.36) [CITATION_3] and length of stay, respectively ( p=0.001).",
